A good length ball, on off. Bumrah defends it onto the pitch.
A full length ball, on middle. Bumrah tucks it to the leg side.
A full length ball, on off. Bumrah defends it out solidly.
A length ball, around off. Shami works it uppishly through the point region for a single.
Runs continue to come for India. A length ball, around off. Bumrah pushes it through the off side for a couple.
A length ball, down the leg side. Bumrah misses his flick.
Full and outside off. Bumrah looks to go after it but misses.
On off, Bumrah defends it out solidly.
A length ball, on off. Shami gets it towards mid-wicket off the inside edge. They take one.
A length ball, around middle, nipping in. Shami misses his flick and gets hit on the pads.
A bumper to end the over. Back of a length ball, on off. Bumrah ducks under it.
Outside off, left alone.
Full, on off. Bumrah keeps it out.
A short ball, on off. Bumrah defends it out solidly.
Back of a length ball, on middle. Bumrah defends it out.
A full length ball, on off. Bumrah pushes it out.
Back-of-a-length ball, on off. Shami stands back and looks to pull it away but misses again.
A short ball, on off. Shami looks to pull it away but misses.
A length ball, outside off. Shami guides it towards point. Jonny Bairstow concedes a couple due to misfield.
Short, on off. Shami looks to pull it away but misses.

A mix-up, but no harm for the tourists. A length ball, on off. Shami looks to work it on the leg side. The ball takes the outside edge and goes towards mid off. Shami wanted a single, but Bumrah was not interested. But when Bumrah thought of crossing, Shami refuses to do the same. The fielder collects the ball and has a shy at the non-striker's end but misses.
A full length ball, on the pads. Bumrah is off the mark on his first delivery, as he tucks it to mid-wicket for a run.
BEATEN! A slower, length ball, around off. Shami looks to defend it out but misses.

In the air, safe! A full length ball, on off. Shami powers it towards long on. James Anderson again looks to go after the aerial ball. The breeze though changes the direction of the ball and it lands safely in front of Anderson. Shami gets two more.

DROPPED! A length ball, on off. Shami moves away and gets under it. He lifts it high in the air, towards mid on. James Anderson comes running under it, grabs the ball, but it spills out. Shami gets two runs. England are not having a good day in the field.
A touch fuller, on the pads. Shami flicks it uppishly towards deep square leg for a couple now.
On middle, Shami defends it out watchfully.
A length ball, on off. Shami blocks it out solidly.
Who will walk out at number 10? It is going to be Jasprit Bumrah.

OUT! CAUGHT! Ollie Robinson comes into the attack and completes his job by getting the wicket of Ravindra Jadeja. This is also the final nail in the coffin. Jadeja's intent was pretty clear, he was going after every ball after getting his fifty. Robinson serves a full length ball, on off. Jadeja stays back and throws his bat at it. He does not middle it though. In fact, he hits it with the toe end of the bat. The ball flies high in the air and goes towards mid off. Stuart Broad runs backward and take a sharp catch by keeping his eyes on the ball.
Commentary.Howout: c Stuart Broad b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Robinson serves a full length ball, outside off. Jadeja looks to go after it but misses.
FOUR! Second boundary of the over. A full length ball, on off. Jadeja rocks back and whips it through mid on for a boundary.
Back of a length ball, on off. Jadeja works it towards gully.
A length ball, on off. Jadeja stays back and pushes it through cover for a couple.
Ollie Robinson comes back into the attack.

FOUR! Jadeja is straightaway on the attack. A length ball, outside off. Jadeja stays back and cuts it through point for a boundary. This also brings up his half century and out comes the sword celebration by Ravindra Jadeja. What a handy innings.
A length ball, outside off. Shami leaves it alone.

Direct Hit and Shami was a goner! A length ball, on off. Jadeja taps it to Rory Burns at gully. He takes off for a single. Burns collects the ball and misses his shy at the striker's end. The batters get one.
A length ball, around off. Jadeja blocks it to the off side.
A full length ball, on leg. Jadeja clips it towards fine leg.
Back of a length ball, on the bodyline. Jadeja looks to pull it away but instead pulls his blade back.
A length delivery, outside off. Shami pushes it through covers. The batters collect three, before the fielder cuts it off.
Serves a length ball, around off. Jadeja throws the sink at it but misses. The ball goes past the off stump.
SIX! Helped away! Anderson fires in a full length ball, on the pads. Jadeja flicks it over the square leg fence for a maximum. Strong hands. The ball is lost in the stands.
A length ball, outside off. Jadeja cuts it through point.

FOUR! Lucky, just over gully. Anderson serves a length ball, around off. The ball takes off after hitting the deck. Jadeja is surprised by the extra bounce. He looks to defend it out. The ball takes the outside edge and goes over the man at gully for a boundary.
A back of a length ball, around off. Jadeja hops and defends it towards point.
A length ball, outside off. Jadeja cuts it towards backward point. Zak Crawley stops it brilliantly.
A touch short, around off. Jadeja pulls it towards square leg for a run. He keeps the strike.
A length ball, outside off. Jadeja dabs it to gully.
Back of a length ball, on off. Jadeja ducks again.
A short ball, on the bodyline. Jadeja ducks under this one.
Hurls a length ball, around off. RJ looks to defend it out but misses. The away movement of the ball makes it difficult for Jadeja to tap it out.
Back of a length ball, on off. Jadeja hooks it towards deep square leg. They pick a couple.
A full length ball, on off. Shami defends it out solidly.
Who will walk out next? It is going to be Mohammed Shami.

OUT! CAUGHT! Joe Root does not drop it this time around. The crowd is bouncing along with James Anderson now. Serves a length ball, just outside off. Thakur looks to defend it out but misses. The ball takes the outside edge and flies to the left of Joe Root, at first slip. He takes a brilliant low catch to his left. India slip further. James Anderson picks up his fourth wicket now. What a game he is having.
Commentary.Howout: c Joe Root b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: A length ball, on off. Thakur defends it out solidly.
Short ball now, on middle. Thakur stays back and looks to pull it away but misses.
A full length ball, on off. Thakur remains solid in his defense.
Serves a length ball, around off. Thakur pushes it back to the bowler.
A length ball, outside off. Jadeja works it towards cover.
A length ball, down the leg side. RJ leaves it alone.
A length ball, outside off. Jadeja shoulders his arms without any second thoughts.
A length ball, around off, coming back in. Jadeja defends it with a straight bat.
Continues with the short ball. This time on middle. Jadeja ducks under this one.
Back of a length ball, down the leg side. Jadeja leaves it alone. The ball ends up with the keeper.
A length ball, on off. Thakur defends it out solidly.
Who will walk out next? It is Shardul Thakur who walks in at number 8.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! James Anderson finally finds the early breakthorugh in the second session. And it's the main man KL Rahul, he trudges back on 84, he will be disappointed with himself. This wicket should help England a lot with their confidence now. Anderson serves a length ball, outside off. It nips in a bit in the end. Rahul looks to defend it out but misses it completely. The ball though kisses the outside edge and goes towards the keeper. Jos Buttler does not drop this one and finally there is some joy in the English camp.
Commentary.Howout: c Jos Buttler b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: A full length ball, on off. Rahul defends it out solidly.
OUCH! That must've hurt. A back of a length ball, on the bodyline. The ball does not get enough bounce off the pitch. Rahul though decides to duck under it but get hit on his back.
FOUR! That is some placement by KL Rahul. A touch fuller, just outside off. Rahul leans in and creams it through the cover region for a boundary.
Anderson fires in a full length ball, on middle. Rahul stays back and clips it through square leg for a couple of runs.

BYE! Back of a length ball, outside off. The ball nips in after pitching. Rahul ducks under it. The ball goes to the left of Jos Buttler, who fails to grab it. The ball goes towards fine leg. The batters sneak a bye. India lead by 16 now.
Back of a length ball, on off. Rahul ducks under this one.
Broad hits the deck hard this time. Serves it on a length, around off. Jadeja works it to the leg side for a single.
Back of a length ball, on middle. Jadeja smartly ducks under this one.

FOUR! Nicely played. A full length ball, on the pads. Jadeja removes his front leg and flicks it through mid-wicket. The fielder gives it a chase, but the ball wins the race to the ropes. He moves to 31.
Serves a back of a length ball, around off. Jadeja goes back and defends it out solidly.
Who will bowl from the other end? It is going to be Stuart Broad.
Around off, Rahul strides forwards and defends it with his inner half.
A length ball, on off. Rahul blocks it out solidly.
A full length ball, on off. Rahul pushes it towards mid on.
A full length ball, on off. Rahul pushes it towards mid on.
LEG BYE! A full length ball, around leg. Ravindra Jadeja stays back and looks to flick it away but misses. The ball clips the pads and goes towards fine leg. They collect a leg bye.
Serves a length ball, on off. Rahul defends it to cover for a single.

Right then. The action to continue post Lunch. England players are in a huddle near the ropes and they disperse into their fielding positions. Followed by the pair of KL Rahul and Ravindra Jadeja, who walk out to continue with their blades. James Anderson to start with the ball.
...Day 3, Session 2...

Right. The scenario is pretty clear now. India lead by 8 runs at the moment and it is not long till their lower-order comes into the question. The tourists will hope that the pair of Ravindra Jadeja and KL Rahul stick around for long and keep increasing their lead. While the Brits will have only one goal and that is to skittle out India as quickly as possible. The next session will prove to be a crucial one. Join us for the action then, as it resumes at 1410 local (1310 GMT).

Even though England bowled really well in the first session, they still find themselves behind in this game! It was Ollie Robinson who struck out Pant in the opening phase of the Day. The seamers enjoyed a lot of movement with the ball, as the weather remained to be overcast. Anderson and Broad kept probing good lines and length but did not trouble the batters much. Sam Curran though, is yet to find his line and length in this game. He has not been up to the mark yet. The English camp expects more from him and would want him to put the batters in some trouble just like the rest of the attack. Their only aim would be to keep chipping wickets, as half of the Indian side is back in the dugout.

India survive the first session. They still have their nose in front! After Day 2 getting affected by rain in the latter stage of the Day. We were off and going into Day 3, and after just 11 balls being served, the rain was back in play. Even they can’t keep themselves away from the game. It turned out to be a start-stop game, and that costed India a wicket. It was Pant who was scratched out early in the day. But then, KL Rahul and Ravindra Jadeja maintained their composure in the middle and they saw the first session of the day not with ease though. There was some miscommunication amongst them in the middle, but they were able to get through that iffy phase.

The dark clouds continue to hover around the ground. A typical English Day. But fortunately, we have finally seen the end of the first session on Day 3, even though it came after some interruptions by the rain. India lead by 8 runs going into lunch.
A full ball, outside off, shapes away very late. Jadeja is not tempted and lets it through to the keeper. That will be LUNCH on DAY 3. India are 191 for 5, and lead by 8 runs.
Serves a very full ball, outside off. Rahul knocks it to the third man for a single.
Around off, on a length. Rahul blocks it on the off side.
Slight fuller and on middle. Jadeja pushes it to mid on and calls for a quick single. Gets it with ease in the end.
Another length ball on off. Rahul punches it past point for a single.
Comes around the wicket and bowls a length ball on middle. Rahul defends it on the off side.
BEAUTY! A length ball, angling across, just around off. Ravindra Jadeja looks to defend but the ball whizzes past the outside edge and to the keeper.
A good length ball on off. Jadeja defends it to covers.
On a length and on the pads, flicked to deep square leg for a brace.
A full ball, slanting across, outside off. Shoulders arms to it.
A good length ball, on the pads. Jadeja misses his flick and gets hit on the pads. Slight appeal for LBW but nothing from the umpire.
Three runs taken! A length ball, around off. Rahul stays back and punches it through point. The fielder chases it and does well to save a single for his team.
James Anderson comes back into the attack now.
Ends the over with a short ball, outside off. Jadeja watches it sail to the keeper.
A touch fuller ball, on middle. Jadeja nudges it to mid-wicket.
Another good length ball outside off and shaping away from the batter. Jadeja lets it through to the keeper.
A good length ball way outside off. Left alone.
Full ball, swinging in, on the pads. Rahul flicks it to the leg side and scampers across for a single. Scores are level now.
On a length and on off. Rahul taps it under his eyes, the second slip catches it on a bounce.
FOUR! Lovely timing! A full ball, angling on middle. Jadeja drives it wide of mid on and the ball races away to the long on fence. India trails by 1 run now.
A pacy short ball on middle. Jadeja sits under it and lets it through to the keeper.
On a length and on off. Jadeja blocks it off the front foot.
Another full ball on off. Jadeja pushes it to covers.
Good leave! A good length ball, angling just around the off stump. Jadeja watchfully leaves it.
A fuller ball, around off. Jadeja pushes it to covers.
EDGY! Serves a full length ball, around off. Rahul looks to defend it out, without moving his feet. The ball take the outside edge and meets the slip on a bounce. Rahul survives.
A good length ball, around middle and off. Rahul blocks it to the leg side.
That's a much better length by Sam Curran. Serves a length ball, around off. Making Rahul play at it. He does so, as he defends it out watchfully.
Hurls a  full length ball, outside off. Rahul pushes it to point, straight to the fielder.
A bit full, on the pads. Jadeja flicks it towards deep square leg for a single. Curran is yet to find his line and length here.
An outswinger this time. Full and around off, swinging away. Jadeja is up to the task and defends it out solidly.
Touch fuller now and outside off, shaping away from the batter. Rahul shoulders arms to it.
BEATEN! On a length and outside off. Rahul takes a big stride forward and looks to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.
A fullish length ball on the pads. Jadeja comes across the line and clips it to fine leg and runs across for a single.
Another full ball on off. Jadeja punches it back to the bowler.
A full ball on middle. Jadeja defends it to the leg side.
Full and on off. Rahul pushes it to sweeper cover for a single.
On a length and on off. Jadeja defends it off the front foot.
On middle, a fuller length. Jadeja tucks it to mid on.
FOUR! Beautiful shot! Curran looks for the swing but bowls it very full and on middle, it shapes away as well. Rahul pushes it straight down the ground and the ball races away to the fence.
Around off, a fuller ball. Jadeja pushes it to covers.
Full and angling on the pads. Jadeja looks to flick but misses. England optimistically appeal but it was clearly angling down.
Sam Curran comes into the attack now. His figures are 7-1-25-0 so far.
Two taken! A full toss, on the pads. Jadeja clips it to deep square leg for a couple of runs.

NOT OUT! A good length ball, around off. The ball straightens up off the deck. Rahul hangs his bat out and looks to defend but misses. The keeper collects the ball and appeals for caught behind straightaway. There was some noise as the ball passed the bat, which gave hope to the English players. So, they take the review and the Ultra edge shows no bat on it. England lose all their reviews.

Review time! This time Joe Root takes a review straightaway for caught behind. The Ultra Edge rolls in and shows that no bat is involved. The on-field decison of not out stands. England though do not have any reviews left now.
Good leave! A short of a length ball on middle. Rahul sways away from it.
A length ball, outside off, shaping away. Rahul shoulders arms to it.
FOUR! Well played! A good length ball on middle. Rahul punches off the back foot through point for a boundary. Jonny Bairstow from point chases it but to no avail.
A length ball on middle. Rahul looks to defend but gets outer half of his bat, towards point.
On a length and way outside off. Rahul watchfully leaves it to the keeper.
Full ball, angling across, outside off. Left alone.
FOUR! Helped away! A length ball, down the leg side. Jadeja clips it fine and well wide of the diving keeper to the fine leg fence for a boundary.
Another good length ball, way outside off. Jadeja leaves it to the keeper.
Length ball way outside off. Jadeja leaves it alone.
Full ball, slanting across, outside off. Jadeja lets it through to the keeper.
Touch fuller and on the pads. Jadeja looks to defend but gets outer half of his blade towards point.
A full length ball, on off. Rahul pushes it past mid off. The batters take a couple before the fielder cuts it out.
A length ball, on off. Rahul defends it to cover and as soon as he does that he yells a NO for a single. Maybe he has learnt his lesson. He is making sure he communicate clearly now.
Nice movement on this one. Serves it on a length, outside off. The ball nips back in. Rahul lets it go to the keeper.
Back of a length ball, on the bodyline. Rahul moves across and looks to pull it away but misses.
Good length ball, outside off. Rahul leaves it alone.
A full length ball, on middle, Jadeja flicks it through the leg side for a single.

JAFFA! Ollie Robinson gets KL Rahul squared up. A length ball, in the corridor of uncertainty. Rahul moves across and looks to defend it out but misses. The ball zips past the outside edge. Ollie Robinson with a top spell this time.
A full length ball, on the pads. Jadeja clips it towards square leg and rotates the strike.
Jadeja is beaten again. This is some good spell from Ollie Robinson. Hurls it on a length, around off, nipping away. Jadeja put his bat  out to block it out but misses it completely.
Good length ball, outside off. Jadeja looks to defend it out. The ball zips past the outside edge.
BEAUTY! A length ball, around off, the away movement continues for him. Jadeja looks to play inside the line but misses.
Good away movement this time. Serves a good length ball, around off, moving away. Jadeja lets it go to the keeper.
A maiden for Stuart Broad. Good length ball, outside off. Rahul does not have any stroke to offer.
A good length ball, outside off. KL Rahul lets it go to the keeper.
A risky leave! Serves a length ball, on the fourth stump line. Rahul wanted to defend it out but pulled his bat back in time. The ball goes past the off stump.
Rahul gets squared up. A length ball, on off. Rahul looks to defend it with a straight bat. The ball though takes the outer half and rolls towards point.
A length ball, around off. Rahul works it towards mid on.
Starts with a full length ball, on off. Rahul blocks it out watchfully.
Stuart Broad comes into the attack now. His figures are 11-1-45-0 so far.
BEAUTY! A length ball, around off, moving away. Jadeja looks to defend it out but misses. The ball whistles past the outside edge.
Effort ball this time. Serves it on a length, outside off. The ball gets an extra bounce after hitting the deck. Ravindra Jadeja pulls his bat back.
A full length ball, on the pads. Jadeja clips it through mid-wicket. The batters take an easy couple.
Serves a good length ball, outside off. Jadeja does not have any stroke to offer.
A length ball, outside off. Rahul lets it go to the keeper.

A direct hit and Jadeja was a goner. A length ball, on off. Rahul pushes it to cover and calls for a run. There is  a bit of a mix-up and Jadeja was late to react to his call. The fielder collects the ball and has a shy at the striker's end. Ravindra Jadeja was not even in the frame when the ball passed the wickets. In the end, the batters get a single.
A full length ball, around off, this one came back in. But, Ravindra Jadeja was equal to the task, as he blocks it back to the bowler. India trail by 29 runs.
Good length ball, outside off. Jadeja shoulders his arms.
Good running! A full length ball, on middle and off. Rahul flicks it towards mid on and takes off for a single.
A good length ball, around off. Rahul taps it to point.
Well left! A good length ball, outside off. The ball stays straight after pitching. KL Rahul watchfully shoulders his arms.
Hurls a length ball, on off. Rahul stays back and defends it out watchfully.
Just a boundary of the over then. Good length ball, outside off. Jadeja lets it go through to the keeper.
Serves it full and just outside off. Jadeja stays back and blocks it to cover.
A full length ball, on off. Jadeja is solid in his defense.
BEATEN! Beautifully bowled. A length ball, outside off. Coming across the batsman. Jadeja looks to defend it out but misses. The ball beats the outside edge.
A length ball, on leg. Jadeja tucks it to square leg.

FOUR! Off the gloves! A length ball, around the hips. Jadeja hops and looks to clip it. The ball though hit his gloves and goes towards fine leg. It races away to the boundary. First runs for Ravindra Jadeja.
A length ball, on off. Rahul defends it out solidly.
FOUR! What a reply by KL Rahul. Anderson dishes it full and outside off. Rahul stays back and drives it square on the off side. It goes through point for a boundary.

Will Joe Root takes it upstairs? No they won't. Serves a length ball, on the fourth stump line, coming back in. Rahul prods and looks to defend it out but misses and gets hit on the pads. Anderson and company make a loud appeal but the umpire is unmoved. England only have a single review left now, so they did not go for it. And smartly enough it worked in their favour, as the replays rolled in and confirmed that the impast was outside the line.
A full length ball, on off. Rahul tucks it to mid-wicket.
Another good length ball, outside off, swinging away, Rahul has no stroke to offer.
A good length ball, outside off. Rahul leaves it alone.
Who will walk out next? It is going to be Ravindra Jadeja.

OUT! CAUGHT! Four, six and out. Ollie Robinson has the last laugh here. Not a great start for India on Day 3, as Pant walks out early. Serves a full length ball, on off. Pant defends it out but with soft hands. He chips it towards cover but straight to the man present there. Jonny Bairstow takes the simplest of catches and Pant has to walk back to the shed.
Commentary.Howout: c Jonny Bairstow b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: SIX! EDGY AGAIN! Back of a length ball, on middle. Pant stays back and looks to pull it away. The ball takes the top edge and flies over the keeper's head. The ball ends up in the boundary at third man for a maximum.

FOUR! EDGY! A full length ball, on off. Pant looks to defend it out. The ball though takes the outside edge and flies past the man at gully. The man there put in a dive to his left, but nowhere near the ball. The ball races away to the boundary.
Hurls a length ball, on off. Pant defends it to cover. He ventures out looking for a single, but was sent back to his crease.
LEG BYE! A touch short, on the pads. Rahul looks to flick it away but misses. The ball clips the thigh pads and goes towards fine leg. They collect a leg bye.
Robinson starts with a back of a length ball, on off. Pant stays back and hooks it towards square leg. They take one. And in no time, the drizzle is back on.
Serves a length ball, on the pads. Pant tucks it through mid-wicket for a single.
A full length ball, on off. Pant defends it out watchfully.

Some appeal strightaway. Back of a length ball, outside off. Rishabh Pant stays back and looks to go after it but misses it completely. The keeper and the slip cordon along with Anderson heard a nick and were jumping in the air, hoping the umpire raises his finger. But the umpire was unmoved. Joe Root has a word with his team-mates and does not go for the review.

The rain stops and the play starts. England players are making their way out in the middle, for the second time within the first hour of Day 3. Followed by KL Rahul and Rishabh Pant who come out to continue with their bat. This time though, James Anderson does not have to wait long to get done with his incomplete over, as he comes steaming in for the remaining three balls.

UPDATE 1145 local (1045 GMT) - We have some good news this time around, hope it stays the same for long. The rain has stopped at Nottingham. The umpires have come to a conclusion to resume the game at 1205 local time. Lets hope the rain gods don't interrupt the game yet again.

UPDATE 1138 local (1038 GMT) - Oh no, not the news anyone would like to hear. The DRIZZLE is back. The covers which were being peeled off a while back and back on the field. And the wait continues. The English weather is playing its own game today.

UPDATE 1129 local (1029 GMT) - We have got some good news coming your way. It looks like the covers are coming off now gradually. If the weather continues to remain the same, we can see James Anderson to continue with his spell in no time. As the game is likely to get underway at 1140 local time.
UPDATE 1127 local (1027 GMT) - The rain seems to have eased out. The umpires are out there having a chat with the groundsmen. The covers are still on so they might be expecting some more weather.

UPDATE 1109 local (1009 GMT) - After just 11 balls into Day 3, the rain gods have no mercy on us. They come into the play again to halt the game today. Lets hope it is just a passing shower. Stay tuned for further updates.
FOUR! Hammered! Pant has taken the attack back to James Anderson. A length ball, on off. Pant dances down the track and slashes it past mid off. The ball races away to the boundary.
A full length ball, around middle and leg. Pant tucks it past mid-wicket fielder for a couple.
Dishes a good length ball, outside off. Pant lets it go to the keeper.
Good away movement to end the over. A good lenght ball, outside off, swinging away. Rahul shoulders his arms.

Some hesitation now. Serves a full length ball, on the pads. Rahul tucks it to mid-wicket and calls for a run. But he sees that the fielder is quick enough to collect the ball. The batter was sent back in the end.
A full length ball, around off, coming back in. Rahul keeps his eyes on the ball and defends it out solidly.
A bit straighter this time. A good lenght ball, just outside off. The ball hold its line after pitching. Rahul shoulders his arms.
Serves a length ball now, down the leg. Rahul leaves it alone. Jos Buttler collects it behind the stumps to his left.
A bit of an away movement to start with. A length ball, outside off, nipping away. Rahul lets it go to the keeper.
Who will bowl from the other end? It is Ollie Robinson who comes into the attack now.
After a day's break, Anderson finally completes his over. A length ball, on the bodyline. Pant tucks it towards mid-wicket.
Right on the money. Serves a full length ball, on off. KL Rahul defends it to cover and rotates the strike straight away.

We are all set here for Day 3. England players stride out to the middle. Followed by Rishabh Pant and KL Rahul to conitnue with their swords for India. James Anderson to steam in and complete his over.

Rishabh Pant, is up for a chat. He says, he was very young when he featured in his first Test game. Adds that he has evolved as a cricketer since the past year. Mentions he played his first game in Nottingham and adds to get  his first century in Oval, is the sweetest part of his journey. Adds that he has been working hard and the results are coming his way. Goes onto say, you need to respect the bowlers here and keep practicing the hard things and never underestimate the opposition. Says he is still a part of a process, it’s just a start of his journey.

PITCH REPORT - Mel Jones is in the middle to go through the pitch, she says, there is a hint of grass on the track. Mentions it is the good length area that the bowlers will try to bowl at. Adds that if the English pacers keep it tight, the outside edge can come into play along with the slips placed behind.

The Indians were probably, actually were surely the happier side of the two when the umpires decided to take the players off. It though is not going to be easy now. One probably feels they will be going for a slightly more aggressive approach. The trail is 58 and they would love to knock this off as quickly as possible. The first hour will be really important.
The England bowlers will be rearing to go, it’s cloudy, you expect the ball to do a bit, they pulled back the momentum on Day 2 and Root will be expecting them to carry forward it here.

It is the moving day of a game which has moved along really quickly. Despite all the rain yesterday and the rain expected going ahead, we can still be hopeful for a result. At present the match is at a knife’s edge. One good partnership will see India hold the advantage. A couple of quick wickets will see the tide shift the hosts’ way.

Rain, rain was everywhere in England yesterday. It was present in Nottingham and also in Manchester where the Men’s Hundred had to be abandoned. The GOOD NEWS HERE TODAY IS, there’s no rain for now, it is dry and we expect play to start on time. Welcome to the coverage of Day 3.
...Day 3, Session 1...

Have to say the game is even stevens right now! India were cruising in the first session. Both Rohit Sharma and KL Rahul never looked like getting out and added 97. However, Rohit's wicket, just at the stroke of Lunch changed things. After the break, England came out all guns blazing. Got three wickets in no time to get back into it. Also, just as their bowlers started causing problems and India were pushed onto the back foot, the rain arrived. Play did restart, once for one ball and the other time for two balls but that was that, the weather then played its part and now we look forward to Day 3. Another day where the forecast is not promising. Let us keep our fingers crossed though. Do join us. Action begins at 1100 local (1000 GMT). Till then, take care and goodbye!

So, the decision has been made! PLAY HAS BEEN ABANDONED! The rain gods had no mercy, it continuously played hide and seek and finally when it came, it just did not stop. The forecast was bad right from the start but we were lucky we got quite some amount of cricket and good cricket is what we witnessed.
The rain has gotten really heavy now! Not good! Yes, we can play until 1930 local but for that, the rain needs to stop.

This is frustrating! The rain is back and the players are off again! We came back for just the one ball before, this time we got two. The wait now continues. It is taking an eternity for Anderson to complete his over. The players are off the field again and the covers are back on.
Length delivery on middle, Rahul nudges it to mid-wicket.
Anderson again steams in and bowls a good length on off, KL Rahul pushes it to point.

Update 1640 local (1540 GMT) - The rains have stopped as of now. The inspection has been done and the play should resume in about 20 mins from now. However, not sure for how long we would go on for as the forecast is not that promising.

And we are off again... Just the one ball after the break. It has started to get heavier and the umpires decide to head back off the field. The covers are on as well. James Anderson has a wry smile on his face as he only got to bowl one delivery after the resumption.
Excellent start after the break! Good length delivery on off, comes back in lately. KL Rahul puts a stride forward and tries to defend. He gets beaten on the outside edge.
We are set to resume! The England players are on the field. KL Rahul is on strike. James Anderson to complete his over.
The umpires are done inspecting the conditions and the news from the middle is that the play will resume at 1615 local (1515 GMT).
Just as I write that, there is some GOOD NEWS! The covers are off which means the rain too has stopped. There is an inspection at 1600 local. If the light is good, we can resume quickly.

Well, we should have had the session after Tea started but it continues to rain and the wait too continues. However, you can catch all the action from the Women's Hundred by switching tabs. Mandhana has just been dismissed but Wyatt is still batting and you would not want to miss that.
It is still raining down in Nottingham and early Tea has been taken. However, difficult to see play resuming after the break. All we can do now is be hopeful.
Update 1500 local (1400 GMT) - We did say there might be a long delay and we are probably right as the rain is now coming down. The crowd is seen holding up umbrellas.
An update - The covers have been got on, it is not raining yet but the umpires are all ready! It has gotten really dark so just assuming, we are in for a long delay here.

What a good one hour of play though after Lunch! We did mention at the start that you won't be disappointed and this was exciting stuff. Really sad that play has been stopped but can't help it. Coming to the game, out of nowhere England are right back into the mix. The wicket of Rohit have opened the floodgates. After the break they have ran through the middle-order thanks to Anderson. They could have easily had Rahul but he was given a life. Nervy times for India and they will probably not mind this halt in play. England on the other hand were just starting to get some momentum and they would have dearly loved to stay out there, especially in such conditions where the ball have started to do a lot. They though, along with us now have to wait for the game to resume.

The umpires have gotten together and after a chat, they have decided to walk back. Not sure if they are going off because of the light or because there is a storm on the way. The light meter is out and a reading has been taken. Really not sure how long this delay will last. The forecast is for some rain so for now, just keeping fingers crossed. We are hearing that they have gone off as the umpires heard thunder so for precautionary measures, they have taken the players inside. However, the announcement was made that play has been stopped for bad light.
An inswinger on off, Rahul defends it off the front foot.
Length delivery on off, Pant taps it to point.
Outside off, left alone by Pant.
Short of a length on middle, Rahul tucks it around the corner for a run.
FOUR! Deft touch! Length delivery on off, KL Rahul guides it with soft hands through the slip cordon to the third man region for a boundary.
On a length on middle and leg, Pant looks to whip it away but misses. He gets hit on the thigh pad and the ball rolls on the leg side. The batters sneak a leg bye.

It has gotten dark out there and the clouds have also gathered above the ground. The floodlights are also on. Broad is back! This is actually good bowling conditions. Things just getting better for the hosts. Can they make use of it?
FOUR! In the gap! Length delivery on off, Rishabh Pant prods and drives it through covers. The fielder gives it a chase but to no success. A boundary.

EDGED BUT SAFE! Good length ball on off, Rahul has a poke at it. The ball kisses the outside edge and flies to the slip cordon. Dominic Sibley attempts to take the catch with a dive but it falls just short of him. It actually was not short, IT DID CARRY! An opportunity goes abegging and that too a big one as it was of Rahul. Could prove costly.
On a length on off, Rahul blocks it out.
Length ball on off, Pant shimmies down and lifts it over covers. The fielder from cover gives it a chase and cuts it off. Three runs taken.
BEATEN! Fuller length outside off, swinging away. Pant tries to drive it but misses.
Length ball outside off, Pant cuts it well but finds backward point.
Good length ball on the fifth-stump line. Pant leaves it for the keeper to collect.
Full and outside off, Rahul leaves it alone.
Short ball on middle, Rahul again sways away from it.
Outside off, Rahul lets it sail through.
Short and on middle, Rahul sways away from it.
Rishabh Pant walks out to bat! Will be interesting to see his appraoch now.

OUT! RUN OUT! Are we witnessing another Indian collapse? Robinson pitches it on a length on off, KL Rahul hops and defends it towards point. He calls for a single but sees Jonny Bairstow coming in quickly and yells a big 'NO'. Ajinkya Rahane meantime has already been halfway down the pitch. He runs back to make it to the crease but Jonny Bairstow is too quick as he fires a throw at the non-strikers' end and hits the bull's eye. Rahane is well out and has to continue his run back to the pavilion. This is the last thing that India would have wanted.
Commentary.Howout: run out (Jonny Bairstow)

Commentary.Commentary: Length ball on middle, Rahane covers his stumps and tickles it to fine leg for a single.
Fuller and outside off, Rahul lets it sail through.
An inswinging yorker on off, Rahul clears his front leg and squeezes it out to point.
Back of a length on off, Rahul pushes it towards point.
Good length ball on off, swinging in. Rahul defends it out.
Good length ball down the leg side, Rahul misses his flick. Good take by Jos Buttler behind the stumps as he dives to his left to collect it.
On a length on off, Rahul taps it to point from the crease.

OVERTHROWS! Rahane is off the mark! A direct hit though and he was a goner too. Back of a length and on off, Rahane looks to drop and run. The fielder at covers runs towards the ball, picks it up and has a shy at the bowler's end but misses. No one backing up and they take three more.
Angled into the pads, Rahul works it through wide mid on for one.
Fuller and outside off, Rahul shoulders arms to this one.
Back of a length and on middle, Rahul nudges it to mid-wicket.
Back of a length and on middle, blocked.

Fifty for Rahul! Back into the side and back amongst the runs! Talk about grabbing an opportunity and he has done well so far. Tough conditions and he has really fought it out well. Needs to go on now. This is fuller and outside off, he guides it through point for two.
Anderson sprays this one well down the leg side, Rahane shoulders arms. The crowd is going bonkers at the moment.
Good length ball on off, Rahane pushes it to covers.
Length delivery down the leg, Rahane leaves it alone. No hat-trick for Anderson but look how the tables have turned.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! The crowd is going bonkers! Anderson is on cloud 9 and so are the English players! They have got Virat Kohli on the first ball. Kohli can't believe it as he holds his ground for a second. What have England had for Lunch! Whatever it maybe, it has surely changed their fortunes. We saw edges fall short and find the gap in the first session. Now, Anderson has managed to find the edge on two consecutive balls and both have carried. All of a sudden, England are back into the game. The first battle of this series between Anderson and Kohli has been won by Anderson. This is on a length and around off, holds its line. Kohli probably could have left it but since he is new to the crease, he wanted to feel bat on ball. He pokes at it, it goes off the outside edge and it is taken by Jos Buttler. India still 79 runs away.
Commentary.Howout: c Jos Buttler b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: Virat Kohli walks out to bat now!

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! James Anderson is always dangerous no matter under what conditions you play in. You cannot keep this man out of this game. Anderson bowls a good length ball on off, nipping away. Cheteshwar Pujara is caught at the crease and has a poke at it. The ball goes off the outside edge and carries through to the keeper. Jos Buttler behind the stumps gulps it down. England are celebrating but the umpires are not sure and they take it upstairs. The soft signal is out. Replay rolls in and Ultra Edge shows there is a spike as the ball passes the bat. Cheteshwar Pujara has to walk back for a timid score. England are all charged up.
Commentary.Howout: c Jos Buttler b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: Have England got a wicket? The umpire does feel it has taken the edge but they have gone upstairs to check if it has carried or no.
On a length on middle. KL Rahul looks to tuck it on the leg side but gets hit on the thigh pad. The ball rolls on the leg side and the batters take a run.
Two! Angled into the pads, this is worked through mid-wicket for a couple.
Another one on a length and around off, kept out.
Gets this one to shape away nicely but the line is outside off, left alone. Another no ball as Ollie Robinson has overstepped.
Fuller and on off, Pujara strokes it back to the bowler.
On off yet again, kept out.
Slightly fuller than the last ball, this time Pujara judges the length well again and blocks it.

England now have an opening! They have been a tad unlucky in this session, they bowled brilliantly, beat the bat several times, found the edges too but it did not go to hand. The desperation also creeped in but they have eventually tasted success and it was Ollie Robinson who got the wicket for them. They need to build on this now, they are still behind in the game but we have seen this Indian batting line-up collapse quite a few times. Are we in for another one here? We will find out.

That wicket right at the end will probably make lunch taste a little, just a little better for England! Well, we say little because, despite that wicket, India are well ahead in the game and all thanks to the brilliance of the two openers earlier on. It was testing conditions to begin with but both Rahul and Rohit showed great fight to grind it out. They took their time and once they got used to the conditions, they started scoring freely just before Rohit was dismissed at the stroke of the break. Rahul though is going strong and the visitors will hope, another partnership can be stitched after the break.

OUT! TAKEN! England strike at the stroke of Lunch! Rohit once again falls in the 30s! Ollie Robinson is absolutely delighted. That gut feeling, we did mention, Ollie Robinson might be the man for England today, yes, he has got just the one wicket but it is the wicket England so desperately wanted and this could well be the opening they needed. Rohit Sharma is gutted as he walks back. He probably could have just let it go to the keeper but this shot is so instinctive, it comes to him so naturally that even unwantingly he ends up playing it. A surprise short one by Ollie! It is a good one too, on the body. Rohit looks to pull but fails to control it, it goes off the top edge and to the fine leg fielder where Curran takes it. A superb opening stand comes to an end. INDIA TRAIL BY 86! THAT WILL ALSO BE LUNCH!

PITCH REPORT - Dinesh Karthik says that India has a vulnerable batting order and on this wicket, there is dry grass. Adds that playing against bowlers who have got over 1000 wickets amongst them (Stuart Broad and James Anderson) is not going to be easy. Mentions that England will need early wickets today.

From making a dream debut, being suspended from playing for your nation and now making a comeback - Ollie Robinson, will be rearing to go and make a mark. Yes, Anderson and Broad will probably be the key but from what we have watched Ollie do in the single game he has played and in the domestic season, something tells me, he could well be the man for England. They though need someone to step up or it would be one-way traffic in this game.

For those who love watching runs being scored, well, Day 2 is probably the best day to bat so you’ll can be in for a real treat. Also, India will be hoping that the movement which was seen yesterday disappears and they get the ideal conditions to bat. They would be wanting to take a good lead as batting last here is extremely difficult and we have seen that in the county games this season.

Let’s now talk about the weather! Well, the weather forecast is not that great for the remaining days of this game. HOWEVER, we begin with GREAT NEWS! It is nice and sunny at the moment so we assume, actually, we are hopeful of getting good game time. So, for those who were more inclined towards white-ball cricket yesterday and missed most of the Test action, the rain gods have had mercy on us so far so tune in and I’m pretty sure it won’t disappoint.

Why has Ashwin been dropped? Why has India gone with 4 seamers? Why have they not stuck to their strength? Why, why, why? All these whys have been answered in some style by the visitors. A superb performance from all 4 pacers and a resilient show from the openers towards the end meant Day 1 belonged to India. It is now time for Day 2, a new day, a new challenge, can India further strengthen their grip on the game or will we see the hosts fight back? We will find out. Welcome to the coverage.

It is India who are in control of this game, but we still have 4 days worth of play remaining and this game could go anywhere if India do not maintain the momentum and keep applying the pressure on England. The action on Day 2 will begin at 11 am local (10 am GMT). Do join us then. Cheers and take care!

Shardul Thakur is up for a quick chat. The Indian seamer says that it was a good day for India. Mentions that they thought they would not get England all out at one point, but the climate was a bit funny and later on, they succeeded in taking 10 wickets. Says that Root was going well, was poised well for a fifty and getting him out was crucial. Adds that Root is one of the best batsmen in the world and it's always a good wicket to have. States that it didn't look like the pitch will take much turn and that's why they chose only one spinner. Shares that he is enjoying bowling in these conditions with the Dukes ball and informs that they had a good preparation in Durham.

There was a lot of chatter regarding India's team selection and whether they needed to drop Ravichandran Ashwin and use 4 pacers, but those questions were shut down perfectly by the Indian pacers. Right from ball one, they probed and asked the right questions and never let the batters feel comfortable. Root was the only one who looked settled, but, apart from him, none of the other batters really had an impactful performance. Jasprit Bumrah once again displayed why his stock value is so much, as he ended with 4 wickets to his name and bowled with a lot of fire. Mohammed Shami would have felt hard done by in the morning session, as he bowled perfectly, getting the ball to shape away from the outside edges multiple times, but he did not get a wicket. But, he kept probing and finished by picking 3 English batters. Shardul Thakur and Mohammed Siraj complemented these two well, as they got 2 and 1 respectively.

England would have wanted to start Day 1 of this 5-game series on a better note, but it was not meant to be for them. In the very first over, Jasprit Bumrah struck and removed Rory Burns and that was the trend for the start and the end of the innings. There were a couple of good stands in the middle phase, with the stand between Joe Root and Jonny Bairstow, of 72 runs, but once Bairstow fell, just at the stroke of Tea, there was a complete collapse for the hosts. From 138/3, they crumbled and got all out for 183. Sam Curran helped England get to that total, as he slammed a few lusty shots towards the end of the innings. With the ball, England bowled decently, but they did not do enough to trouble the pair of Sharma and Rahul. The hosts failed to take a single wicket and would have been slightly happier had they sent one of these two back to the shed.

What a wonderful day of cricket we have witnessed between England and India. The Indian openers, Rohit Sharma and KL Rahul have done very well, as they have hung in there and have survived 13 overs towards the end of the day, and have come out unscathed. At the end of Day 1, it will be the Indians who will be the happier of the two sides, as they are in control of this game, at this point.

Angled into the body, nudged to the leg side.

FOUR! Beauty. Sharma gets his second boundary. He is not going to miss out on those. Fuller, outside off, Rohit Sharma leans and gently pushes this one past the point fielder. There is a chase, but the ball wins the race.
Length delivery, outside off, left alone.
Full on off, RS pushes it back to Broad, who collects the ball and mimes a throw back towards Sharma.
Another good delivery! A short of a length ball, outside off, it rears up after hitting the deck, RS looks to poke at this but fails to get any bat.
A back of a length ball, around off, tapped to the off side.
FOUR! That will go to the ropes. His first boundary. On a fuller length, around off, KL Rahul strokes this one through covers and finds the fence.

Well bowled by Jimmy! Makes KL play at it and he gets beaten. Angles in a length delivery, around off, it shapes away late, as KL looks to defend inside the line. The ball flashes past the edge to the keeper.
Way outside off this time, KL lets it be.
Rohit judges if they can take the single and he gets it. Around off, on a good length, Rohit taps this to covers and they run hard to complete the run.
An away swinging ball, outside off, Sharma leaves it untouched.
Another good delivery! Fuller, outside off, KL Rahul looks to defend inside the line, but as he is away from the ball, it goes to the keeper without any issues.
This is closer to the off pole, on a length, KL Rahul gets his front foot ahead, but watches the ball go past him, to the keeper.
Another length delivery outside off, KL does not go fishing after this.
Outside off, Rahul makes no effort to play at that.
Again, KL is in a hurry to get off the strike and get those quick runs. Around off, pushed to covers. Rahul wanted the run, but his partner sent him back.

BYE. That's very well bowled. On a length, outside off, the ball hits the deck and shoots up. Rohit Sharma looks to defend, but the ball whistles past the edge to Buttler, who is not able to judge this well and is not able to pouch. A bye is stolen.
Maiden from Jimmy! On a length on off, defended out.
Around off again, back of a length, dabbed to point.
That's a good call by Rohit. There wasn't a run there. Around off, on a length, Rahul taps this to point. Comes ahead, wanting the single, but Sharma sends him back.
Same length as the previous ball, but this is bowled wider outside off, it is nipping away as well. KL Rahul looks to defend inside the line and the ball goes unharmed to the keeper.
Drags his length back and serves a back of a length ball, outside off, KL Rahul goes back and raises his blade, leaving it alone.
Did you know? 183 is England's lowest team total against India in England in the first innings of a Test.
Around off on a fuller length, eased to the point fielder.
Outside off, on a length, Rohit Sharma shoulders arms.

Good running! KL is up and running too. That will make him feel much better. On a length, around off, KL Rahul leans ahead and pushes this through cover-point. They take two and then decide to take the third as well.
Broad goes for the fuller and wider ball for the third time in a row. KL again is not tempted into the shot and leaves it.
An action replay of the previous delivery. KL again raises his blade and allows the ball through.
The artificial lights are switched on.
Goes fuller this time, but wider too. KL Rahul leaves this one untouched.
Starts off with a good length delivery, around off, KL goes back and taps this to the off side. Rahul is quick to deny the single as well.
Stuart Broad to share the new cherry from the opposite end. Four slips await...
4 from the first over, then! Outside off, on a length, RS makes no attempt to play at that.
Good length ball, around off, shaping away, Sharma taps this to the point region.
Fuller and wider outside off, Rohit Sharma leaves this one alone.
Angled into middle and leg, on a length, Sharma plays this with an angled bat to the leg side.

EDGY FOUR! Sharma gets off the mark in a streaky manner. So close to getting Sharma, was Jimmy! On a length this time, around off, again, there is away movement, Rohit Sharma looks to push this through the covers, but the outside edge is induced. The ball runs away past the gully region to the third man fence.
Starts off with a fuller length ball, around off, the ball shapes away slightly, but Rohit is solid in his defense, as he pushes it to the off side.
We are set for the chase. The England playes stride out to the middle. Followed by KL Rahul and Rohit Sharma, who come out to bat for India. James Anderson to start with the ball.

The new ball did the trick for India! The tourists started the final session on a very good note, courtesy of Shardul Thakur. Then there was a phase, where they kept leaking runs. But once the new ball came into play, it changed their fortune. Bumrah rose to the occasion and he went onto to complete his 5-fer. Thakur and Siraj also snared two wickets in this innings, while Shami bagged a single wicket. The onus is now on the batters to chase down the target of 209 runs and take a 1-nil lead in this Pataudi Series, 2021. Do join us, as the chase gets underway in a while.

Things did not work out, how the hosts wanted it to be! England were put on the back foot straightaway into the initial phase of the final session. Jos Buttler was the first one to depart, that too right in the first over after continuation. Although, it was their skipper who lead from the front. He went onto score a century. The only positive performance from the England camp. Then it looked like Root and Curran could do a lot with the bat and tilt the game in their favour. But once the new ball came into play, the English players could not stay away from the collapse. And they lost their grip over the match.

What a comeback by India, they have become the masters of come back in the past year! Take a bow! Jasprit Bumrah, is back ladies and gentlemen. India need 209 runs to take a 1-0 lead in this Test series. The sun is out now, and it surely is a batting pitch at the moment. India would love to take an advantage of it and go back unscathed at the end of Day 4.

OUT! CAUGHT! There is the last wicket that India badly wanted. And Mohammed Shami finally gets a wicket. Good length ball, on off. Ollie Robinson swings hard but gets a top edge and the ball goes straight to Ajinkya Rahane at third man. Excellent field placement from Virat Kohli there as Ajinkya did not have to move an inch to take this catch. England are bowled out for 303.
Commentary.Howout: c Ajinkya Rahane b Mohammed Shami

Can Jasprit Bumrah wrap things up in the last ball of the over. Lets find out, he is on a Hat Trick.

The fiery contest between Siraj and Curran ends here. And, Siraj with that catch has the last laugh. England slip further.

The final session of Day 4 is set to begin. The Indian players are in a huddle near the ropes, they spread out into their respective fielding positions. Followed by Joe Root and Jos Buttler, who walk out to bat for England. Shardul Thakur to start with the ball.

So, the final session of the day is right around the corner. Will the rain play its part in today's play? Or will the clouds also play the role of a spectator, just like all of us? A lot of cricketing action yet to come your way, as we get a clear picture of how this Test game will turn out to be. Do join us in a short while to catch the action.

India made a good come back in the second session! It was Bumrah who struck early and got the better of Sibley. After the early wicket, it was not looking good for India. They gave away 116 runs in this session, which shows they were struggling to stem up the run flow. Bairstow and Root were taking India for a ride. But the former had to depart, as Siraj was successful in hunting him down. Thakur also went on to pick up his first wicket of the innings. Although, near the end of the second session, a few dark clouds were hanging around the ground, which started to have an impact on the ball. The tourists will hope the conditions remain the same in the final session of Day 4.

Root continues to hold the team together! Root has been a constant spectator from one end, since he came on the field.  England have half of their side sent back to the dugout. They lost Sibley in no time in the second session. Bairstow then came in to add some important runs to their lead but could not survive for long. The onus now lies with Root and Buttler, to use their experience and take their team to safer shores. Their only aim would be to keep increasing the lead and not loose too many wickets in the final session of the day. They currently lead by 140 runs.

What a session of cricket we have witnessed here. Two sessions, without any rain. Pinch me, I think it’s a dream. Anyways, the game was tilting from one end to the other. In my opinion, it seems that the session is shared equally amongst the two teams.

Right then. It's all happening here at Trent Bridge. A close contest between both the sides. The second session of the Day 4 will play an important role and give us a clear mapping of how this game will turn out to be. Do join us for the same, as the game resumes at 1340 local (1240 GMT).

The advantage slipped out of their hands! India started off on a really good note. In the first hour of the play, they were on top. And this was due to the efforts of Siraj and Bumrah, as they found two crucial wickets of Burns and Crawley respectively. But after that, the bowlers were successful in troubling Sibley and Root. They surely got the edge into play, but it was not enough. They could not break the defense of Root and Sibley, as the conditions did not favour them. The pacers are struggling to get the ball moving, as the sun is out and it is bright. The Indian bowlers need to be patient, as they know that a couple of quick wickets can get them back into the game.

A good recovery by the English skipper, Joe Root! England went back unscathed on Day 3, but this feat was destroyed by the Indian pacers in the first session itself on Day 4. England lost two wickets in quick succession of Burns and Crawley. It looked as if, there was another collapse on its way. But Root and Sibley were not going to give up easily. Root played an aggressive role, once he came on. While, Sibley keeping things slow at his end. It can be seen on the scorecard as well. Root bagged his 51st Test half-century. The sun is out and you can’t ask for better conditions to bat on. They lead by 24 runs going into Lunch on Day 4. England will love to make the most off it and swell their lead.

We have witnessed an uninterrupted first session on Day 4, looks like all the prayers to keep the rain away worked. You can say that India were on top in the beginning. But, Root and Sibley have clearly taken the advantage over the tourists.

England really got going in the second session on Day 3. It was Robinson who started the proceedings on Day 3 by getting the better of Pant. This Test also marked Robinson's come back from a suspension, and what better way to make a statement, than picking up his first 5-fer in Test cricket. While, Anderson is proving that he ages like a wine, as he picked a four-wicket haul. Broad and Curran were also good with the ball but they remained wicketless. They bundled out India, but with a lead of 95 runs.

India came out to bat on Day 3 with Rahul and Pant starting their day, but soon after the game was halted by it's best friend, the showers. Rahul's composed innings of 84 runs, was much-needed for him, to prove his worth. Then it was Jadeja who picked things up from where Rahul left off. But once Jadeja fell it looked like, India were in a bad position. As, we all know that India generally carry three number 11 batsmen, who are place in the bottom three of the batting line-up, had a very poor average coming into this game. But my word did Bumrah not take us for a ride? The tail-enders whacked 48 runs to swell the lead to 95 runs.

It was raining sixes! Oh wait, it was just raining. Yet again on Day 3, it was the rain which ended the day just like what happened on Day 2. It's not surprising at all, keeping in mind these are the English conditions. This was bound to happen. But the pace at which this test has gone, we are surely on track to get a result out of this game. We expect the play to start on time and expect to squeeze in three sessions, with/ without the rain. Welcome to the coverage of Day 4.

India on the other hand, need to be patient, they just have to hit the right lines and lengths. A wicket or two quickly can surely create panic in an England set-up which has not been that great with the bat. Still, a result is well and truly possible as we have two more days to go. There is rain forecast on both the days but let us hope we get enough cricket to squeeze in a result. Do join us at 1100 local (1000 GMT). Till then, take care and goodbye!

A whole-hearted performance from Rahul and the lower-order of the Indians helped them take a really good lead. However, England fought back hard second time around with the bat. They just did not surrender and have managed to not lose a wicket. However, they will need to keep doing so on a wicket which seems to have eased out a little. Can they capitalize and put up a good show with the bat?

England snared the necessary wickets early on in the second session, but it wasn't enough. It was James Anderson to start the proceedings in the second session and he went on to get two wickets in quick interval to put India on the back foot. Soon after, Robinson got the better of Jadeja, and then it looked like the bowlers will continue their magic and get rid of the tail within no time. But that's not how it turned out to be. The bowlers kept probing good lines and lengths, but Bumrah made sure that he was on top of it. England leaked some crucial runs in the end. But it was their star with the ball, Ollie Robinson who got a fi-fer to end things for India. Then, the batters came out and saw out 6 overs into their innings and they remain unscathed at 11 runs.

Surely, India will be a happier side going into Tea on Day 3. India did not start the Day on a good note, as they lost Pant at the start. But Rahul and Jadeja did enough to take the team to a comfortable position, as they were then healing from the early wickets which they lost in this innings. In the end, it were the tail-enders who swelled the lead to 95 runs, India were missing the tail-attack since a long time now and today was the right time for them to shine and make the session completely in favour of India.

That's your lot for this Test match. It was a thorough entertainer but unfortunately didn't reach the climax. We are expecting more similar action (minus the rain) in the coming games. The first ball will be at 11 am local (10 am GMT) but you can join us in advance for the build-up. Until next time, it's goodbye and cheers!

JOE ROOT, THE ENGLAND CAPTAIN, IS THE PLAYER OF THE MATCH. He says that it was a great Test match and the weather has robbed them of a close game and hopes that they can take the good stuff from this week to the rest of the series. Believes that they would have had nine opportunities to take wickets, had they played, but it is a shame that the weather did not let them have any action. Tells that there are certain areas which they want to work on and they want to take all the chances they create and they have to show strong character. On the scheduling of cricket in England, with The Hundred going on and no First-class cricket right now, Root tells that they have to deal with this issue, until the schedule changes and for the experienced players, who had to come from white-ball cricket to the Test format, it would have been easier to adapt, but, for the younger guys, it is slightly tough. Stresses that this is not an excuse, but opines that it could be challenging. Root says that he enjoyed his hundred and there was a lot of enjoyment as to how he played in this game. Adds that India have a really good seam attack and from his point of view, he looked to attack the bowlers and feels like he got into a good rhythm early in his innings.

Virat Kohli, the Indian captain, says that this is a bit of a strange one and they wanted a crack at the total, but it is a shame that the weather did not allow the game to continue. Feels that they wanted to start strong and heading to Day 5, they felt like they had the chance to win and felt like they were on top in the game. On the way the openers played late on Day 4, he says that they wanted to play with intent and it was not about survival and their intent kept them ahead in the game. Shares that the bowlers have been in the nets for the last three and a half weeks and they got a lead of 95 just due to their effort and he thinks they did a tremendous job with the blade. On whether this team will be the template for the series, Kohli thinks that this should be the template but adaptability has been their strength. Hopes that they get some exciting cricket for the remainder of the series.
It's raining but we will have the presentation...

England also had a few positives from the match but there are more negatives for them. Their top order batting needs a serious look-in, while the middle order is also looking fragile. Only Joe Root stood up with the bat to take the challenge to the Indian bowlers. That's surely not enough if you want to take down a team like India. James Anderson is aging like fine wine and his bowling spell on Day 2 was incredible. Ollie Robinson is another bowler who continues to show that he belongs to this level.

Positives for India! The batting of their openers, KL Rahul in particular. If Mayank Agarwal recovers from his concussion, that would be a real headache for Virat Kohli, ignoring KL after such a good Test match will be tough. The quartet of Indian pacers dominated the show. Jasprit Bumrah led the pack with a 9-wicket haul but the other three pacers were equally impressive if not more. Ravindra Jadeja getting preferred over Ravichandran Ashwin didn't have much of an impact with the ball but his knock with the bat justified his selection in a way.

Who will be hurting more? India or England? You can argue for both sides here. 157 on the final day with 9 wickets in hand, you will have to back the batting team to do the job. Having said that, with the conditions being overcast and England possessing some great bowlers for this particular condition, you never know, 2-3 early wickets and that would have put the cat among the pigeons. It's hard to guess what would have happened and it's a really sad end to this intriguing Test match.

It was a fascinating Test match. The first day will be remembered for the English collapse in the last session when India seized the initiative. Day 2 brought us rain but in a little window of play, James Anderson roared to remove Cheteshwar Pujara and Virat Kohli off consecutive balls. The moving day was all about more rain and the Indian tail wagging to gather vital runs. The penultimate day of this Test match was very engrossing with Joe Root leaving his mark with a century and Jasprit Bumrah claiming a 5-wicket haul to make it nine wickets in the match. No one will argue that had there been no rain, this Test match would have become even more interesting as the rain gods snatched momentum from both teams at some point in time.

Right then, Day 5 has been completely washed out and this Test match ends in a draw. That means both India and England will get 4 points each in the ICC World Test Championship table. What a shame! It was one heck of a Test match and was heading towards a close finish but the rain gods decided to spoil the party and have robbed us of a possible humdinger. 157 runs were needed on the final day but not a single ball was possible.

Michael Atherton has a chat as well! He says that the weather is terrible and it is pretty bleak outside and he thinks that the Indian fans will be hoping that it clears quickly enough. He says that the forecast is not too good but says that these grounds have a good drainage system and opines that India would need around 30-40 overs to chase this down, and he hopes that the rain dies down by mid-afternoon, at the very least. On Ollie Robinson, he says that due to Archer's injury, Robinson's inclusion was easier and it was a good start by him and he will complement Broad and Anderson well. Feels that England have some decisions to make around that top order and it is tricky as well, as there is no First-Class cricket being played at this point, so there is no opportunity for any players to come and replace the batters at the top of the order. Adds that Zak Crawley showed good talent against Pakistan, but, since then, he has had an average of just 11, so Atherton feels that the selectors need to have a look at the same and make some decision. Feels that Dawid Malan could come in, not to open, but in the middle order. Praises KL Rahul and Rohit Sharma as they played very well late on Day 4. On India chasing this down, he thinks that getting through that late hour on Day 4 was key and India did well in that phase and he thinks that batting will not get that harder today.

Joe Root gives a quick interview. Tells that it was very special to enjoy with the crowd again and terms the atmosphere unbelievable. Feels that to get there and score a century is quite special, especially in the context of the game. Root keeps this knock of his right up there and mentions that it was against a very good attack on a wicket that has offered something to the bowlers throughout the whole game. Shares that he felt in good rhythm, somewhere near his best and hopes to use that for the rest of the summer. Further adds that his feet were going really well and he had quite a proactive mindset from the start and tried to put the bowlers off their lengths. Mentions that as a group, you need to realize the joy of scoring runs and it's really important. On their plans for Day 5, Joe replies that they have to make it as hard as possible for India. He wants to defend runs but at the same time keep catchers in. Feels that throughout the game, it has been very tough to start an innings and they could very easily get two or three early wickets. States that the thing in their favour is that India have the pressure of batting on a fifth-day pitch. Signs off by saying that it is a great reminder of why Test cricket is the pinnacle of the sport and you don't get ebbs and flows like this in any other format.

Update 11.15 am local (10.15 am GMT) - The irritating drizzle is on. Moments back, Virat Kohli was on the ground and he was having a word with the umpires. Jasprit Bumrah comes up for a quick chat! The speedster says that he felt good after his performance on Day 4 but adds that the more important day is today and they want the weather to clear and the game to begin. Regarding the changes in the bowling conditions, Bumrah replies that it felt soft in the first innings and swung all day but it was slower in the second innings and they had to figure the length to swing the ball. On his unusual bowling action, Bumrah tells that he has not always followed instructions and believes that if he has something different, he will keep that as an advantage. Regarding the feeling that white-ball cricket is easier to take up as a youngster, Bumrah says it's not easier with the amount of cricket they play, but comparatively, white-ball cricket is easy and Test match takes a toll on your body as a fast bowler. Adds that when he was growing up it was all about Test cricket and mentions that this format is the most rewarding. Further adds that you put in a lot of effort and then get the result and this reward stays with you. On his injuries, Bumrah shares that his most serious injury happened before he played for the country. On his routine, Bumrah replies that he tries to keep a balanced diet, sleep well, focus on recovery and train well. Regarding his issues with the no balls, Bumrah answers that when you get tired, you push forward and you can go a little over the line and this is one aspect he wants to improve on. When asked about the last technical change he has done in his bowling, Bumrah informs that when he came to England in 2018, he used to have an outswinger but never used it but under these conditions, he backed his outswinger and tried to use it in the game. Also shares that during the break, he spent time with the family and took a break from cricket to come with a fresh mindset. On his batting and that particular pull shot for a six, Bumrah says that he has been working hard on his batting and he wants to contribute runs as a lower-order batsman.

Let's paint the scenario of how things stand as we enter the final day of the Test. India have been set a total of 209 by the English Lions and around 1/4th of the same has been handled by the trio of KL Rahul, Rohit Sharma, and Cheteshwar Pujara. An absolute beauty from Broad saw him remove KL towards the fag end of the day, but it is definitely India who are in control of this game. Hello, folks! After 4 days of riveting cricketing action and some bouts of rain as well, we have finally arrived at the endgame of the first Test between England and India. With the forecast that we had been looking at for the entirety of the Test, it would be hard to visualize that we would arrive at Day 5 and we could have a chance of a result. But, both these teams have fought tooth and nail and we have a real chance of either one of these two teams to take home the first round.

Right then. That's it from Day 4. It's been a fantastic day of Test cricket. The first session was in the favour of the hosts. The second session was shared. But the last session truly belonged to India. India are on their way of becoming the comeback kings in cricket. Only if they are able to chase down the remaining 157 runs. Day 4 for India! The Indians bowlers had to bundle out England by the end of Day 4 and well, they certainly did that. The job was done, thanks to the brilliant effort with the ball by Jasprit Bumrah. He bagged a 5-fer and it was only achievable once the new cherry was handed to him. Throughout the day, whenever India saw a partnership building up, they managed to break it. They picked up 2 wickets in the first session. Three in the second session. And they went on to end this early in the final session by picking the remaining 5 wickets. Then, came the time for the batters to seal the deal. India got off to a good start, with the help of Rahul and Rohit. But now the onus lies on Cheteshwar Pujara and Rohit Sharma to come back on Day 5 and ends things with ease for India.

A recap of Day 4! The England batters walked with the task of turning the deficit into a lead. But, they started off on the wrong foot. Because of the departure of Burns and Crawley in quick succession. Joe Root and Sibley ensured they kept adding runs and they did not lose a wicket till Lunch. But soon after Lunch, Sibley departed. Root though remained a constant figure in this English camp he went on to score a century and again he was the one dragging his team up and back into the game. There were some short partnerships to support him in the middle. But once Root feel, the wickets just kept falling for England and they put on a target of 209 runs for India to chase.

A huge burden on the English seamers! The England bowling line-up has to defend 157 runs on Day 5, with India having 9 wickets in hand. It's a tough ask from them. Anderson never looked to trouble the batters much in his short spell. But once Robinson came into the attack, he hit the deck hard and caused some problems but it was not enough to snare a wicket. In the end, Broad managed to draw the first blood, which got the crowd rally behind them and made sure to end the day for the hosts on a positive note. But will it be enough, that's the main question.

The RA-RO cruise continued, but for a short while! The Indian openers picked up from where they left off. Rahul and Sharma, were yet on another mission, as they were building a foundation of the chase. But the former had to depart early after a great innings. Rahul was literally toying with the bowlers today. Then came Cheteshwar Pujara, who did his job of seeing off the day along with Rohit Sharma, without losing any more wickets. India end Day 4 at 52 for 1. They need 157 runs more to win the game and take a 1-nil lead in this series.
